40 years Video Game Sales Analysis and predicting sales for different countries

Group Member - Vaishnavi Dubal, Jason Trotman, Maheswara Reddy, Prachi Rathod

Introduction

Overview

Video games have had a great impact on our childhood since we grew up playing video gmaes and all are still very much attached to our childhood memories and try to relive it by playing the newer version of the older games. We have see that the video game industry has changed a lot during the last forty years and we will be analyzing the Video Game sales and critic/users overview of these games based on their genre, PLatforms, publisher, developers. The data that we are using for this project contains data from year 1980 - 2020. We will be exploring the dataset to see any trends in the data and do exploratory data analysis to gain insights from the data.

Business Problem

We will predict the Video game sales of a for sales in Japan, Europe, North America, Global and other basesd on the Year of Release features.

Dataset Overview

The data is from public data recourse: Kaggle

The data set structure demonstrates that it has 16 features and around 16719 records of Video Games across Japan, Europe, North America, Global and other from the year 1980 - 2020.

The predictor variables are described below:

-Name It mentions the name of the game -Platform The platform that published the game -Year_of_Release The release date of the game -Genre Games have different genres, such as Sports, PLatform, Action, puzzle, this column talks about the different genres -Publisher The companoes who published the game -NA_Sales Sales of video games across North America -EU_Sales Sales of Vidoe games accorss Europe -JP_Sales Sales iof Vidoe games across Japan -Other_Sales Sales of countries other than North America, Europe, and Japan -Global_Sales Global sales of video games -Critic_Score The scores that critics of the game ranging from 1 - 100 -Critic_Count No.of critics who rated the game -User_Score Users who gave ratings to the game from the range 1 -100
-User_Count No.of users that rated the game
-Developer Developers of the game -Rating Ratings such as AO, K-A, M, E, T, E10+, EC+, RP

Approach

  • We will be using the training dataset to train our model and test dataset to predict the sales of the video

  • We will conduct data cleaning and perform an exploratory data analysis to generate some insights influence of the following ratings, year of release, frequency of games in the specific years on the sales of the video game:

  • We plan to develop a Linear Regression model and make use of the arima forecast model to predict the behavior of video game sales in the coming years

  • We will be using the RMSE and variance score as a metric to determine the performance of model in terms of prediction

How ratings have affected the Global sales of the data

#Ratings vs sales
ratings_vs_sales <- sqldf('select Rating, avg(global_sales) as average_global_Sales from data where Rating is not null group by Rating order by average_global_sales desc')
ggplot(data = ratings_vs_sales , aes(x = reorder(Rating, -average_global_Sales), y = average_global_Sales)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(x = "Rating" , y = "average global sales" , title = "Ratings vs Average global sales")

From the above analysis we can that the games with rating AO i.e Adults only have the highest video game sales along with K-A Kids to Adult followed by Mature, Everyone and Teen.

The Games which have RP i.e Rating Pending have the lowest sales globally

Initial Linear Regression with categorical variables

Many of the independent variables in the video game dataset are categorical fields. These categorical fields also have many unique values so it makes sense to run a couple of regressions on them initially to see if they are even useful.

The first categorical variable is Publisher. Running a linear regression with Publisher as a factor variable (dummy variables) shows that none of the publishers differ from the others in a statistically significant way.

global_sales_lm_publisher <- lm(Global_Sales~factor(Publisher), data=video_game_sales)

A time series is a sequence where a metric is recorded over regular time intervals. Depending on the frequency, a time series can be of yearly (ex: annual budget), quarterly (ex: expenses), monthly (ex: air traffic), weekly (ex: sales qty), daily (ex: weather), hourly (ex: stocks price), minutes (ex: inbound calls in a call canter) and even seconds wise (ex: web traffic).

We have already seen the steps involved in a previous post on Time Series Analysis. If you havent read it, I highly encourage you to do so.

Forecasting is the next step where you want to predict the future values the series is going to take.

But why forecast?

Because, forecasting a time series (like demand and sales) is often of tremendous commercial value. In most manufacturing companies, it drives the fundamental business planning, procurement and production activities. Any errors in the forecasts will ripple down throughout the supply chain or any business context for that matter. So its important to get the forecasts accurate in order to save on costs and is critical to success.

Conculsion

Based on our analysis, as we obserevd that the sales of the video games decreased with recent years, based on how the gaming industry has eveolved, we had a hypothesis that with in the coming years there is going to be a decrease in the video games sales in the coming years, since there are very less people who prefer having a physical copy of game, with extreme developements in technology, people in the future wont face the problem of memory space, hence the people who will opt for the physical copies of the video games are the people who have a knack to collect the physical copies of the games and are looking for discounts. Other sales that would be generated would be through digital selling of the games, similar to what we have been opting for more recently.
